Problem 1. (8 points)

Your first problem involves graphical summaries of categorical data. One such summary is called a barplot. A barplot looks like a histogram (in fact a histogram is a type of barplot), but the functions you use to generate the graphics are different and designed to work with different types of data: A histogram deals with continuous numeric data, and a barplot deals with categorical data. The functions used are hist() and barplot() respectively. The two functions also differ in how they process the data. The function hist() is expecting a vector of numeric values which it divides into equal-sized bins before counting and then displaying. In contrast, barplot() is expecting data in a very specific fashion. We will use the table() function (discussed in Chapter 12 of your book) to process our raw data into a format usable by table().

Plotting a frequency table

We generate a frequency table using the table() function:

table(NHANES$smoker)
## 
##   yes    no 
##  4126 25249

and then use R’s defaults to plot the tabulated results:

plot(table(NHANES$smoker),xlab="smoker?",ylab="count",main="Smoking behavior in the participants of the 1999-2004 NHANES Study")

This graph is missing a few details that might be important for our audience to properly interpret the data: Perhaps we want to tell them how many participants were in the study or how many of those subjects are not included in the graph because their entry had a value of NA value.

Let’s figure out the following:

  • How many subjects are in the NHANES study,
  • and how many of those had a missing value for $smoker.

There are many ways to extract that information (summary() works just fine, for example), but I want to introduce you to a technique that is far more flexible and that we will generalize to more complicated situations in future assignments (so make certain you understand how this works):

length(NHANES$smoker)
## [1] 31126
sum(is.na(NHANES$smoker))
## [1] 1751

As you can see, the number of subjects, 31,126, is the length() of the smoker variable (which I will often refer to as $smoker to remind you that the data is stored in a column named smoker in some data-frame.). Perhaps a bit more mysterious is the expression that calculates the number of missing values as 1,751. This expression makes use of a very convenient feature of R– namely that the values TRUE and FALSE are converted to 0’s and 1’s in an expression that expects a number.

Let’s step through this idea:

  1. The expression NHANES$smoker is a vector of values (of type factor).
  2. The function is.na() applies a test to each in turn– asking “are you an NA (missing value)?”.
  3. This generates a vector of logicals.
  4. Applying sum() to the vector of logicals turns the TRUE values into 1, and the FALSE values into 0, then adds them.

Together, these 4 steps have the effect of counting the number of TRUE’s. Reread that last paragraph then see if you can make sense of what follows:

head(NHANES$smoker)        # original values
## [1] no  no  no  no  yes no 
## Levels: yes no
head(is.na(NHANES$smoker)) # TRUE for NA's, FALSE otherwise
## [1] FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE
sum(is.na(NHANES$smoker))  # Count the number of TRUE's
## [1] 1751

Now let’s graph our table and include this supplementary information using the sub= argument. Please note that I am using plot() and not barplot() (that comes later). The difference is important:

plot(table(NHANES$smoker),xlab="smoker?",ylab="count",main="Smoking behavior in the participants of the 1999-2004 NHANES Study",sub="31,126 observations total (1,751 of these were missing values)")

Honestly I am still not satisfied with this graph (now we are moving into aesthetics). If the number of levels is too small then plotting a table with this technique creates an image with too much empty space (at least to my mind). Let’s fix that problem using barplot():

barplot(table(NHANES$smoker),xlab="smoker?",ylab="count",main="Smoking behavior in the participants of the 1999-2004 NHANES Study",sub="31,126 observations total (1,751 of these were missing values)")

A warning: The function barplot() works well for categorical data, and it even serves reasonably well when the data has a natural order (ordinal data) to it (think ‘first’, ‘second’, and ‘third’), however you are responsible for ensuring that the data is in the proper order. Even more importantly– it is also up to you to deal with missing values or uneven spacing between the columns. The first nested expression that we used, plot(table()), is better for numeric data– particularly when there are more than just a few values.

Problem 2. (25 points)

The table() command can produce contingency tables as well. It’s easiest to understand with an example:

table(NHANES$smoker,NHANES$ethnicity)
##      
##       Mexican American Other Hispanic Non-Hispanic White Non-Hispanic Black
##   yes              838            185               1972                961
##   no              7240           1161               9543               6273
##      
##       Other/Multi
##   yes         170
##   no         1032

A mosaic plot (see http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mosaic_plot) is a great way to visually detect associations between categorical variables that might be hidden inside the numeric data of the table.

mosaicplot(table(NHANES$ethnicity,NHANES$smoker),main="Smoking behavior",ylab="smoker",xlab="ethnicity")

The areas are proportional to the values in the contingency table. The rectangle with the largest area (Non-Hispanic White’s that don’t smoke) corresponds to 9543– the largest number in the contingency table.

Problem 5. (7 points)

At that last site, the term “age-corrected” appeared fairly frequently… perhaps there’s something strange about the ages in our data. Let’s start by looking at the ages of everybody. As usual, we’ll use table() to prepare the data for barplot(), and access the variables (cols) in a data frame using the dollar-sign $ construction:

barplot(table(NHANES$age),xlab="age (in years)",ylab="count",main="barplot of age distribution for NHANES study")

We can also use boxplot() to view a summary of the data without using table().

boxplot(NHANES$age,ylab="age (in years)",main="boxplot of age distribution for NHANES study")

If the variable doesn’t have too many distinct values (or any skipped values) then a barplot can still be very informative for discrete numeric data… The plot(table()) construction is a bit smarter– it will leave a gap when ages are missing– something the barplot() command does not do unless you personally prepare the data yourself.

When the number of possible values in the variable grows too high then a barplot() becomes uninformative– a histogram may be a better way to look for patterns in the values, however, for a bird’s-eye view, the boxplot() works no matter how complicated the data. It is useful for a broad overview, but it hides many of the details. However, it is very easy to produce multiple boxplots of a variable that are broken down by category:

boxplot(NHANES$age~NHANES$sex,ylab="age (in years)",main="boxplot of age distribution for NHANES study")

or, here by smoking:

boxplot(NHANES$age~NHANES$smoker,ylab="age (in years)",main="boxplot of age distribution for NHANES study")

Problem 6. (18 points)

Hey! Not only did we find a strange peak in the ages of the study participants, your latest side-by-side boxplot shows that the age distribution of Non-hispanic White’s is fundamentally different than the other ethnic groups. Let’s learn how to limit our data.

R has many, many ways of extracting data that satisfies some collection of criteria. We can use one variable in a data frame to categorize another variable in the same data frame (like we did in the boxplot() examples. This time we want to make a new table with a smaller number of entries. Let’s do that for each of the sexes and make distinct barplots (not boxplots) of the ages– one for each sex.

Let’s start by looking at the first few entries in the age column and the first few entries in the sex column:

head(NHANES$age)
## [1]  2 77 10  1 49 19
head(NHANES$sex)
## [1] female male   female male   male   female
## Levels: male female

It’s a bit hard to see which entries are supposed to line up, so I’ll show you the first few in table form:

##   age    sex
## 1   2 female
## 2  77   male
## 3  10 female
## 4   1   male
## 5  49   male
## 6  19 female

We can limit which entries make it to the barplot() function (for display) by using the square brackets, []. In the example below, the variable NHANES$sex is compared to the value “female”. Every NHANES$age for which NHANES$sex is “female” will be kept. It’s essentially the same thing as we saw in the first problem– NHANES$sex=="female" is a vector of logicals… each age that lines up with a TRUE will be kept, and the rest discarded:

head(NHANES$age[NHANES$sex=="female"])
## [1]  2 10 19 59 11 38

See how that works? Now we can pass this off to barplot():

barplot(NHANES$age[NHANES$sex=="female"],main="barplot of female ages",xlab="age",ylab="count")

Wait! that looks horrible! What happened? Oh, right we need to prepare the data using table():

barplot(table(NHANES$age[NHANES$sex=="female"]),main="barplot of tabulated female ages",xlab="age",ylab="count")

Now, if we want to show BOTH we can use the table() function to prepare the data, but this time we will use more arguments:

barplot(table(NHANES$sex,NHANES$age),main="barplot of tabulated ages",xlab="age",ylab="count")

Hmph… I see several problems. First, we have no way of knowing how to interpret the colors, and second, we have generated a stacked barplot– sometimes this is fine, but other times (particularly when the data is not particularly smooth), it can be a bit hard to tell what’s happening.

Let’s fix the first problem using the legend=TRUE named argument:

barplot(table(NHANES$sex,NHANES$age),main="barplot of tabulated ages",xlab="age",ylab="count",legend=TRUE)

As for the second– we can use the beside=TRUE named argument:

barplot(table(NHANES$sex,NHANES$age),main="barplot of tabulated ages",xlab="age",ylab="count",legend=TRUE,beside=TRUE)

That’s a bit better… although we are coming dangerously close to the limits of what the human eye can discern. A few things, however, are immediately obvious– the number of women is higher in the 19-35ish range than the men (and also in the oldest segments of the populations).
